#!/usr/bin/env zsh
# Iterate through a PRD and implement all issues while AFK
set -e

# TODO: We should define the number of iterations as 10, or be able to pass with
# --iterations
# We should stop if not in a git repo
# We assume that there is a plans/prd.json file containing all the issues
# We also assume there is a plans/progress.txt file, append-only, where agents add their updates

# We then iterate 10 (or --iterations) times
# Each time, we tell claude:
#
local claudePrompt="
Check @docs/worktrees/prd.json and @docs/worktrees/progress.md.
Find the highest priority issue to work on and work on only that one.
You decide which one is the highest priority, it doesn't have to be the first
one.

Details of issues are in ./docs/worktrees/issue-*.md files.
You must follow tdd principles while developing the issue: start with a failing
test.

Only work on one issue.

Once done, update progress.md with what you accomplished this session, which
tests you completed, any issues discovered or fixed and what should be worked on
next.
"

# - @plans/progress.txt
# - @plans/prd.json
# - Find the highest priority feature to work on and work on only that feature.
# - You decide which is the highest priority, not necesarily the first one
# - Write tests that proves the feature doesn't work
# - Ensure tests are RED
# - Implement the feature
# - Ensure tests are GREEN
# - Update prd.json and progress.txt
# - Commit your changes
# - Ask a reviewer to review
# - Implemente their feedback if relevent
# - Ensure tests are still GREEN
# - Update prd.json and progress.txt
# - Commit again
# - If you notice the PRD is done, echo <promise>PRD COMPLETE</promise>
#
# We echo the result.
# If the result contains <promise>PRD COMPLETE</promise> we stop before the end
# of the loop
# Otherwise we keep iterating
